placement/objects/allocation_candidate.p.message:
Aha! I found one that breaks:

(3A): same_subtree({G1.1, C2, R})
 - check_these = {G1.1, C2, R}
 - ancestors_G1.1 = {G1.1, C1, R}
 - ancestors_C2 = {C2, R}
 - ancestors_R = {R}
 - common_ancestors = {G1.1, C1, R} & {C2, R} & {R} = {R}
 - check_these & common_ancestors = {G1.1, C2, R} & {R} = {R}
 - return True

(3B): same_subtree({G1.1, C2, R})
 - check_these = {G1.1, C2, R}
 - ancestors_G1.1 = {G1.1, C1}  <== l@@k, {R} is missing!
 - ancestors_C2 = {C2, R}
 - ancestors_R = {R}
 - common_ancestors = {G1.1, C1} & {C2, R} & {R} = {}
 - check_these & common_ancestors = {G1.1, C2, R} & {} = {}
 - return False

So generically, to trigger this problem, you have to have a "hole" in the ancestry tree. That is, the ancestry line of a provider involved in the request hits a provider *not* involved, and then hits another provider that *is* involved.

> Do you mean we would think `grandchild` is a root not `child`?

I... don't think so? I think I meant this:

If the grandchild is involved in the request, but the child is not, then when we recurse to build the ancestry for the grandchild, we'll do this:
- grandchild.parent => child
- child.parent => not in the dict, so assume None, and stop.

We only notice this if there is more than one "empty" (i.e. not involved in the request) tier above the provider for which we're trying to calculate ancestry.

I still haven't fully noodled how (or even if) this would affect the same_subtree calculation. Lemme go do that now...

[Later]

Okay, so we're first intersecting the "ancestry lines" for all the providers we're checking for same_subtree-ness. This identifies all and only their common ancestors. By definition this first intersection should *always* include the root (ignoring sharing).

Then we see whether any of the providers we're checking are in that set of common ancestors. (Actually I believe there can be at most one.) If so, we declare same_subtree to be true.

Using this example:

              R
            /   \
          C1     C2
         /  \      \
      G1.1  G1.2   G2

Scenarios (A), when the ancestry dict is fully populated:

Scenario (1A): same_subtree({C1, G1.1})
 - check_these = {C1, G1.1}
 - ancestors_C1 = {C1, R}
 - ancestors_G1.1 = {G1.1, C1, R}
 - common_ancestors = ancestors_C1 & ancestors_G1.1 = {C1, R}
 - check_these & common_ancestors = {C1, G1.1} & {C1, R} = {C1}
 - This is nonempty, return True

Scenario (2A): same_subtree({C2, G1.1})
 - check_these = {C2, G1.1}
 - ancestors_C2 = {C2, R}
 - ancestors_G1.1 = {G1.1, C1, R}
 - common_ancestors = ancestors_C2 & ancestors_G1.1 = {R}
 - check_these & common_ancestors = {C2, G1.1} & {R} = {}
 - This is empty, return False

========
So what happens if that first intersection stops too early? It would exclude providers not involved in the request... but the second intersection would be excluding those anyway.
========

Scenarios (B), when the ancestry dict only includes providers involved in the request:

Scenario (1B): same_subtree({C1, G1.1})
 - check_these = {C1, G1.1}
 - ancestors_C1 = {C1}  (*not* R)
 - ancestors_G1.1 = {G1.1, C1}  (*not* R)
 - common_ancestors = ancestors_C1 & ancestors_G1.1 = {C1}
 - check_these & common_ancestors = {C1, G1.1} & {C1} = {C1}
 - This is nonempty, return True

Scenario (2B): same_subtree({C2, G1.1})
 - check_these = {C2, G1.1}
 - ancestors_C2 = {C2}  (*not* R)
 - ancestors_G1.1 = {G1.1, C1}  (*not* R)
 - common_ancestors = ancestors_C2 & ancestors_G1.1 = {}
 - check_these & common_ancestors = {C2, G1.1} & {} = {}
 - This is empty, return False

==============

So after all that, I'm pretty sure it totally doesn't matter, and this (by serendipity, not intent) was a valid optimization.

I'm pretty sure Chris's gabbi test [1] covers this ground, but it's pretty hard to rationalize at that high a level. So IMO it would be worthwhile to have unit test coverage. We already have test_check_same_subtree which exercises (A); it should be pretty easy to twiddle its parent_by_rp dict to exercise (B).


[1] https://review.opendev.org/#/c/676204/

